<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ910201-0033</DOCNO><DOCID>910201-0033.</DOCID><HL>   Business Brief -- Philip Morris Cos.:   Firm to Spend $400 Million   To Expand Tobacco Plant</HL><DATE>02/01/91</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE C10</SO><CO>   MO</CO><IN>TOBACCO PRODUCTS (TOB)</IN><LP>   Philip Morris Cos. said it will spend $400 million toexpand its tobacco plant in Cabarrus, N.C. The expansion,which is the largest that the New York-based tobacco gianthas undertaken since 1982, primarily reflects the strength ofits overseas tobacco business.   &quot;The export business -- particularly to Asia -- is boomingand the U.S. business is right on target,&quot; said WilliamCampbell, chief executive officer of Philip Morris USA, thecompany's tobacco unit. Philip Morris's international salesgrew nearly 16% in 1990 and &quot;we have no reason to feel thatwe won't have a similar kind of year next year,&quot; theexecutive said.</LP><TEXT>   The expansion, which will be completed in 1994, willincrease tobacco capacity to 125 billion units, up from 85billion units. The 1,800-employee plant will add 660 workers.   &quot;This is a big deal, when you consider that this industrywas perceived as the next steel industry where plant closureswere a way of life,&quot; said John McMillin, an analyst atPrudential Bache.</TEXT></DOC>